  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are statutes that address money laundering in many countries around the world. In the United States, the primary federal statutes that address money laundering are found in the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** of 1970 and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** of 1986, which is codified in **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957**.\n\n### Key U.S. Statutes on Money Laundering:\n1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**:\n   - This statute makes it a federal crime to knowingly conduct or attempt to conduct a financial transaction involving the proceeds of unlawful activity with the intent to promote the carrying on of illegal activity, to evade taxes, or to conceal the nature, source, or ownership of the proceeds.\n   \n2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**:\n   - This statute prohibits engaging in monetary transactions in criminally derived property valued at more than $10,000, regardless of whether the individual intended to promote illegal activity or conceal the transaction.\n\n3. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**:\n   - The BSA requires financial institutions to maintain records and file reports that are useful in detecting and preventing money laundering, such as Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs) and Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs).\n\n### International Efforts:\nMoney laundering is also addressed internationally through frameworks such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Many countries have implemented laws and regulations in line with FATF recommendations.\n\n### Examples from Other Countries:\n- **United Kingdom**: The **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)** is the primary legislation addressing money laundering.\n- **Canada**: The **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA)** governs anti-money laundering efforts.\n- **European Union**: The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs) that member states must incorporate into their national laws.\n\nThese statutes and frameworks aim to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds and integrating them into the legitimate financial system.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
